  "timeframe": "1D / 4H / 15m (multi-timeframe)",
  "market_context": "ETH had printed three consecutive daily expansion candles into a higher time frame point of interest, suggesting exhaustion. The next day was anticipated to form a reversal off previous day high rather than continue in the same direction.",
  "key_observation": "After three daily expansion candles, the 4-hour formed a candle 2 closure sweeping previous day high with a shallow wick supporting downside expansion, enabling a 15-minute IFVG entry using a series of fair value gaps as the change in state of delivery.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the daily, identified three expansion candles into a point of interest and decided not to trade in the same direction, looking for a reversal instead.",
    "Step 2: Determined the reversal would form off previous day high and dropped to the 4-hour to look for the sweep.",
    "Step 3: On the 4-hour, confirmed a candle 2 closure sweeping previous day high with a shallow wick supporting expansion lower.",
    "Step 4: Dropped to the 15-minute to apply the fractal model using inversions; first considered an IFVG near previous day high but waited for confirmation.",
    "Step 5: After a new high formed, marked out a series of fair value gaps and waited for a closure through all of them (not just one) as the change in state of delivery.",
    "Step 6: First attempt failed to close through both FVGs, saving a loss; waited for a new high and re-evaluated with a single FVG inversion.",
    "Step 7: Once price rejected the inversion and quickly closed back below it, took the short entry with stop on the swing high, targeting 2R toward the lower end of the range."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade reached 2R target, though price came close to stopping out — noted as something to be mindful of for stop placement.",
  "lessons": "Top-down alignment (daily bias → 4H structure → 15m entry) combined with using a series of FVGs (not just one) as the IFVG confirmation filters out false reversals and protects against losses when only one gap is breached.",
